"When women have defined that they are going to get a divorce, they really go for it," says Varona. "They prepare techniques for the separation, they already have another place to live for themselves and for their children, and they have already preserved some resources (in savings and financial investments or in a partner's company) that will allow them to have the financial autonomy that they need to survive as a single mother." In addition, she says, just like they have been preparing the actual separation, women have had in mind that their decision to divorce will also be followed by a legal divorce. "After separating from their partner," she explains, "they continue to count on him financially, in many cases, making it unnecessary, for both of them, to get a divorce for many years. And letting a divorce 'cool' after a separation makes it more difficult for courts to take sides because they don't have to consider the wife's possible dependence on her former husband for economic support. On that point, these cases are easier for judges."
